<DOC><DOCNO> AP881122-0264 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0032EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-OilPrices     11-22 0230</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0240</SECOND><HEAD>Oil Prices Edge Higher Pending OPEC News</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Crude oil traders are moving cautiously as OPECoil ministers continue meetings aimed at resolving the cartel'sproduction crisis.   Prices edged higher Monday in light trading on the New YorkMercantile Exchange. Contracts for January delivery of West TexasIntermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, rose 7 cents from Friday'sclose to settle at $12.98 cents per barrel.   Among refined products, the December contract for heating oilgained 0.71 cent to 43.47 cents per gallon, while the Decembercontract for unleaded gasoline lost 1.33 cents to 44.32.   Traders attributed the drop in gasoline prices to the end of a10-day-old refinery strike in Brazil.   OPEC ministers adjourned their formal talks after 90 minutesMonday to continue private negotiations among key members who aretrying to work out a lengthy dispute between Iran and Iraq.   One of the main obstacles to a new agreement among the 13 membersof the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries has been Iraq'sinsistence on a production ceiling equal to Iran's.   OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman opened the cartel's winter meetingby appealing for compromise. He said members must reach a new accordlimiting their oil production or risk a ``serious erosion'' of crudeprices.   Analysts said they expected market trading to be light in advanceof clearer signals from the ongoing talks.</TEXT></DOC>